Add next appender into logback.xml to colorize logs output:

    &lt;appender name=&quot;STDOUT&quot; class=&quot;ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender&quot;&gt;
            &lt;!-- encoders are assigned the type
                 ch.qos.logback.classic.encoder.PatternLayoutEncoder by default --&gt;
            &lt;encoder&gt;
                &lt;Pattern&gt;%d %highlight(%-5level) [%thread] %cyan(%logger{15}): %msg%n&lt;/Pattern&gt;
            &lt;/encoder&gt;
    &lt;/appender&gt;

In addition to using a colored `ConsoleAppender`, you could also color the statement itself.  Note this has limitations and may not work with all systems.  It worked well for internal projects, particularly when you want to log that a major task in a chain is complete or simply while debugging errors.

To quote [an external link][1]:

    System.out.println(&quot;\u001B[31m&quot; + &quot;the text is red&quot; + &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;);

`\u001B[31m` is the ANSI code to color the output red and `\u001B[31m` is the ANSI reset command.

    public class ColorLogger {
        
        private static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(ColorLogger.class);
        
        public void logDebug(String logging) {
            LOGGER.debug(&quot;\u001B[34m&quot; + logging + &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;);
        }
        public void logInfo(String logging) {
            LOGGER.info(&quot;\u001B[32m&quot; + logging + &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;);
        }
        
        public void logError(String logging) {
            LOGGER.error(&quot;\u001B[31m&quot; + logging + &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;);
        }
    }

In your case, it sounds like you can try to write the contents of the aggregated log out and optionally color each statement by finding each string that concerns you.  

This can alternatively just be done by printing it to an HTML page and using CSS selectively on your text.

  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/java-log-console-in-color

In Java, you can add color to your console output by using ANSI escape codes. These codes provide a way to manipulate the text appearance in the terminal, including changing the text color. However, keep in mind that not all terminals support ANSI escape codes, so make sure the one you are using does.

To print colored logs, you can create a helper method that appends the appropriate ANSI escape codes to the log messages. Here&#39;s a simple example of how to do that:

    @Slf4j
    public class ColoredLogger {
    
        // ANSI escape codes for text colors
        private static final String ANSI_RESET = &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_BLACK = &quot;\u001B[30m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_RED = &quot;\u001B[31m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_GREEN = &quot;\u001B[32m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_YELLOW = &quot;\u001B[33m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_BLUE = &quot;\u001B[34m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_PURPLE = &quot;\u001B[35m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_CYAN = &quot;\u001B[36m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_WHITE = &quot;\u001B[37m&quot;;
    
        // Log levels
        public enum LogLevel {
            INFO(ANSI_GREEN),
            WARNING(ANSI_YELLOW),
            ERROR(ANSI_RED);
    
            private final String colorCode;
    
            LogLevel(String colorCode) {
                this.colorCode = colorCode;
            }
    
            public String getColorCode() {
                return colorCode;
            }
        }
    
